Here's my recommended approach:

## 1. Full WordPress Backup (Essential)

**Database + Files:**
```bash
# On your server, export the database
mysqldump -u username -p database_name > hiiiwav_backup_$(date +%Y%m%d).sql

# Download wp-content folder (themes, plugins, uploads)
# Use SFTP/SCP or your host's file manager
```

**Or use a plugin** (easier):
- **UpdraftPlus** - creates full backup you can download
- **All-in-One WP Migration** - single file export, great for local restore

## 2. Static Archive (View-only, no WordPress needed)

```bash
# HTTrack or wget to mirror the entire site as static HTML
wget --mirror --convert-links --adjust-extension --page-requisites \
  --no-parent https://hiiiwav.com -P ./hiiiwav-archive
```

This gives you a browsable static copy you can open in any browser. Commit to a separate repo like `hiiiwav-wordpress-archive`.

## 3. Local WordPress Instance (Full functionality)

**Easiest options:**
- **Local by Flywheel** (free) - drag and drop import
- **MAMP/XAMPP** + manual DB import
- **Docker**:

```yaml
# docker-compose.yml
version: '3'
services:
  wordpress:
    image: wordpress
    ports:
      - "8080:80"
    volumes:
      - ./wp-content:/var/www/html/wp-content
  db:
    image: mysql:5.7
    environment:
      MYSQL_DATABASE: wordpress
      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: password
```

## 4. SEO Preservation (Critical)

Create a redirect map from old URLs → new URLs. I see you already have some redirect work in `.specstory/history/`. 

**For this new site**, you'll want a `_redirects` file (if using Netlify) or handle it in your router:

```
# Example _redirects
/old-wordpress-page/  /new-page/  301
/blog/old-post/       /blog/new-post/  301
```

**Get all your current URLs first:**
```bash
# Crawl and extract all URLs
wget --spider --recursive --no-verbose --output-file=urls.log https://hiiiwav.com
grep -oP 'https://hiiiwav\.com[^\s"]+' urls.log | sort -u > all_urls.txt
```

Or use **Screaming Frog** (free up to 500 URLs) for a proper crawl with response codes.

---

## My Recommendation

1. **Now**: Install UpdraftPlus, do a full backup, download it
2. **Now**: Run `wget --mirror` to create static archive → push to `hiiiwav-wordpress-archive` repo
3. **Now**: Export URL list for redirect mapping
4. **Before launch**: Set up 301 redirects in your new site
5. **Keep**: Database backup + wp-content folder stored safely

The static archive is the lightest option for "I just want to see what it looked like." Local WordPress is only needed if you want to actually interact with it (edit posts, test plugins, etc.).

Want me to help you set up the redirect mapping based on your current WordPress URL structure?

---

## 301 Redirects Explained

**301 = "Moved Permanently"**

When someone (or Google) visits an old URL like `hiiiwav.org/fest`, the server responds with:

```
HTTP/1.1 301 Moved Permanently
Location: https://hiiiwav.org/projects/hiiiwav-fest
```

The browser automatically goes to the new URL. The user barely notices.

### Why it matters for SEO:

1. **Link juice transfer** - Google passes ~90-99% of the old page's ranking power to the new URL
2. **No broken links** - Old bookmarks, social media links, and backlinks still work
3. **Index update** - Google eventually replaces the old URL with the new one in search results

### The status codes in your redirects:

| Code | Meaning | Use Case |
|------|---------|----------|
| **301** | Moved Permanently | Old page exists at new location |
| **302** | Moved Temporarily | Temporary redirect (don't use for migrations) |
| **410** | Gone | Page intentionally removed, won't come back |

### Example from your `_redirects`:

```
/fest                    /projects/hiiiwav-fest  301
/cart                    /                       410
```

- `/fest` → tells Google "this content now lives at `/projects/hiiiwav-fest`, update your index"
- `/cart` → tells Google "this page is gone forever, stop indexing it"

### Without redirects:

- Visitors get 404 errors
- Google sees broken pages, ranking drops
- All those backlinks you've built become worthless

The `_redirects` file I created will be read by Netlify (or Vercel with some config) and handle this automatically when you deploy.

+ /**
+  * Migrate WordPress images to Supabase Storage
+  * 
+  * Prerequisites:
+  * 1. Create a public bucket named "uploads" in Supabase Storage
+  * 2. Add NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL and NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY to .env.local
+  * 
+  * Usage: npx tsx scripts/migrate-images-to-supabase.ts
+  */
+ 
+ import { config } from 'dotenv'
+ import { resolve } from 'path'
+ config({ path: resolve(process.cwd(), '.env.local') })
+ 
+ import { db } from '../db'
+ import { posts, pages } from '../db/schema'
+ import { eq } from 'drizzle-orm'
+ import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js'
+ import * as fs from 'fs'
+ import * as path from 'path'
+ 
+ const SUPABASE_URL = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL
+ const SUPABASE_ANON_KEY = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY
+ const WP_UPLOADS_PATH = '/Users/boskombp16/Local Sites/hiiiwav-wordpress-local/app/public/wp-content/uploads'
+ const BUCKET_NAME = 'uploads'
+ 
+ if (!SUPABASE_URL || !SUPABASE_ANON_KEY) {
+   console.error('❌ Missing NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL or NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY in .env.local')
+   process.exit(1)
+ }
+ 
+ const supabase = createClient(SUPABASE_URL, SUPABASE_ANON_KEY)
+ 
+ async function extractImageUrls(): Promise&lt;Set&lt;string&gt;&gt; {
+   const allPosts = await db.select().from(posts)
+   const allPages = await db.select().from(pages)
+   
+   const urls = new Set&lt;string&gt;()
+   
+   ;[...allPosts, ...allPages].forEach(item =&gt; {
+     // Cover images
+     if ('coverImage' in item &amp;&amp; item.coverImage?.includes('hiiiwav.org/wp-content/uploads')) {
+       urls.add(item.coverImage)
+     }
+     
+     // Images in content
+     const imgRegex = /https?:\/\/hiiiwav\.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/[^\s\)\"\']+/g
+     const matches = item.content.match(imgRegex) || []
+     matches.forEach(m =&gt; urls.add(m.replace(/[)\]"']$/, ''))) // Clean trailing chars
+   })
+   
+   return urls
+ }
+ 
+ async function uploadImage(wpUrl: string): Promise&lt;string | null&gt; {
+   const relativePath = wpUrl.replace('https://hiiiwav.org/wp-content/uploads/', '')
+   const localPath = path.join(WP_UPLOADS_PATH, relativePath)
+   
+   // Check if file exists locally
+   if (!fs.existsSync(localPath)) {
+     console.log(&#96;  ⚠️  Not found locally: ${relativePath}&#96;)
+     return null
+   }
+   
+   // Read file
+   const fileBuffer = fs.readFileSync(localPath)
+   const mimeType = getMimeType(localPath)
+   
+   // Upload to Supabase
+   const { data, error } = await supabase.storage
+     .from(BUCKET_NAME)
+     .upload(relativePath, fileBuffer, {
+       contentType: mimeType,
+       upsert: true
+     })
+   
+   if (error) {
+     console.log(&#96;  ❌ Upload failed: ${relativePath} - ${error.message}&#96;)
+     return null
+   }
+   
+   // Return public URL
+   const { data: urlData } = supabase.storage
+     .from(BUCKET_NAME)
+     .getPublicUrl(relativePath)
+   
+   return urlData.publicUrl
+ }
+ 
+ function getMimeType(filePath: string): string {
+   const ext = path.extname(filePath).toLowerCase()
+   const mimeTypes: Record&lt;string, string&gt; = {
+     '.jpg': 'image/jpeg',
+     '.jpeg': 'image/jpeg',
+     '.png': 'image/png',
+     '.gif': 'image/gif',
+     '.webp': 'image/webp',
+     '.svg': 'image/svg+xml',
+   }
+   return mimeTypes[ext] || 'application/octet-stream'
+ }
+ 
+ async function updateDatabaseUrls(urlMap: Map&lt;string, string&gt;) {
+   console.log('\n📝 Updating database URLs...')
+   
+   // Update posts
+   const allPosts = await db.select().from(posts)
+   for (const post of allPosts) {
+     let updated = false
+     let newContent = post.content

+     
+     // Update cover image
+     if (post.coverImage &amp;&amp; urlMap.has(post.coverImage)) {
+       newCoverImage = urlMap.get(post.coverImage)!

+   for (const page of allPages) {

+     let newContent = page.content
+     
+     for (const [oldUrl, newUrl] of urlMap) {

+       }
+     }

+     if (updated) {

+       console.log(&#96;  ✓ Updated page: ${page.slug}&#96;)
+     }
+   }
+ }
+ 
+ async function main() {

+   console.log(&#96;📁 Local WordPress uploads: ${WP_UPLOADS_PATH}&#96;)
+   console.log(&#96;☁️  Supabase URL: ${SUPABASE_URL}&#96;)

+ # WordPress to Next.js Migration Playbook
+ 
+ &gt; Step-by-step guide for migrating WordPress sites to Next.js with Supabase  
+ &gt; **Status:** In Progress | **Last Updated:** December 7, 2024
+ 
+ ---
+ 
+ ## Overview
+ 
+ This playbook documents the complete process of migrating a WordPress site to a modern Next.js stack. It's designed to be repeatable for future WordPress → Next.js migrations.
+ 
+ ### Tech Stack
+ - **Frontend:** Next.js 15 (App Router)
+ - **Database:** Supabase (PostgreSQL)
+ - **Storage:** Supabase Storage
+ - **Hosting:** Vercel
+ - **ORM:** Drizzle
+ 
+ ---
+ 
+ ## Pre-Migration Checklist
+ 
+ - [x] Access to WordPress admin
+ - [x] Access to WordPress hosting (Kinsta, WP Engine, etc.)
+ - [x] Domain registrar access
+ - [x] Supabase account created
+ - [ ] Vercel account created
+ - [x] Local development environment set up
+ 
+ ---
+ 
+ ## Phase 1: Backup &amp; Archive ✅
+ 
+ ### 1.1 Create Static Archive
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ # Mirror the entire WordPress site as static HTML
+ wget --mirror --convert-links --adjust-extension --page-requisites \
+   --no-parent --reject "xmlrpc.php,wp-login.php,wp-admin/*" \
+   -e robots=off https://your-site.com/
+ 
+ # Commit to a separate repo for safekeeping
+ git init
+ git add -A
+ git commit -m "WordPress archive - $(date +%Y-%m-%d)"
+ git remote add origin https://github.com/you/site-wordpress-archive.git
+ git push -u origin main
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ **Automation opportunity:** Script that takes a domain and creates the archive repo automatically.
+ 
+ ### 1.2 Export URL List for Redirects
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ # Extract all URLs from the mirrored site
+ find site.com -name "*.html" | sed 's|site.com||' | sed 's|/index.html||' | sort -u &gt; url_list.txt
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ ### 1.3 Download Full Backup from Host
+ - Export database (&#96;.sql&#96; file)
+ - Download &#96;wp-content&#96; folder
+ - Store in local WordPress environment (Local by Flywheel)
+ 
+ **Completed:** 
+ - Static archive: &#96;hiiiwav-wordpress-archive&#96; repo
+ - Local WordPress: &#96;/Users/boskombp16/Local Sites/hiiiwav-wordpress-local/&#96;
+ 
+ ---
+ 
+ ## Phase 2: Database Setup ✅
+ 
+ ### 2.1 Create Supabase Project
+ 1. Go to https://supabase.com/dashboard
+ 2. Create new project
+ 3. Note the project ID and region
+ 
+ **Project details:**
+ - ID: &#96;pzoyeigicwgmmlngxowj&#96;
+ - Region: &#96;us-west-2&#96;
+ 
+ ### 2.2 Configure Environment
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ # .env.local
+ DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.[project-id]:[password]@aws-0-us-west-2.pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres"
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ ### 2.3 Push Schema
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ npm run db:push
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ **Automation opportunity:** CLI tool that creates Supabase project and configures env vars automatically.
+ 
+ ---
+ 
+ ## Phase 3: Content Migration ✅
+ 
+ ### 3.1 Import Posts &amp; Pages
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ # Fetches all content via WordPress REST API
+ WP_BASE=https://your-site.com/wp-json/wp/v2 npm run wp:import
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ **What gets imported:**
+ - Posts → &#96;posts&#96; table (title, content, excerpt, cover image URL, tags, SEO fields)
+ - Pages → &#96;pages&#96; table (title, content, SEO fields)
+ 
+ **Content is converted:**
+ - HTML → Markdown (via Turndown)
+ - Dates preserved
+ - Slugs sanitized
+ 
+ **Completed:** 21 posts, 29 pages imported
+ 
+ ### 3.2 Verify Import
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ npx tsx scripts/check-db-content.ts
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ ---
+ 
+ ## Phase 4: Image Migration 🔄 IN PROGRESS
+ 
+ ### 4.1 Create Storage Bucket
+ 1. Go to Supabase Dashboard → Storage
+ 2. Create bucket named &#96;uploads&#96;
+ 3. Set to **Public**
+ 
+ ### 4.2 Add Storage Credentials
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ # Add to .env.local
+ NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL="https://[project-id].supabase.co"
+ NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY="your-anon-key"
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ ### 4.3 Run Image Migration
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;bash
+ npm run wp:migrate-images
+ &#96;&#96;&#96;
+ 
+ **What this does:**
